
---
name: cite-links
description: |
  Enforce safe URL handling using the Fact ID pattern: Claude collects sources and writes drafts using opaque IDs only. A deterministic Python script — not Claude — does the final URL substitution, making hallucinated links structurally impossible.

  Trigger this skill when:
  - User asks for research with citations or sources
  - User asks Claude to include links or references in a document
  - Any task combining web search (WebSearch/WebFetch) with document generation
  - User asks to "cite sources", "add references", or "back this up with links"
---

## Why This Matters

If Claude writes URLs inline — even at the end, even "just to resolve" — it can still hallucinate them. The URL was grounded earlier in context, so it's *less likely* to be wrong, but "less likely" is not a guarantee. The only way to make hallucinated links **structurally impossible** is to ensure Claude never writes a URL at any stage. A Python script handles substitution instead.

---

## Sequencing Rule (read before starting)

**Fetch first. Write second. Never invent a registry entry.**

These phases must run in order. Do not begin writing until all sources for the document have been fetched. Do not create a registry entry for a source you have not actually retrieved — if you couldn't fetch it, it gets a `[SRC:MISSING]` citation, not a made-up entry. An invented registry entry is indistinguishable from a hallucinated URL.

After completing Phase 1, proceed directly to Phase 2 — no confirmation needed.

---

## Phase 1 — Research: Build the Fact Registry

When fetching any web source via WebSearch or WebFetch, register it immediately in a fact registry JSON file. Save the registry at `fact_registry.json` in the project's research folder.

**Fact ID format:** `SRC:[short_snake_case_description]`
- Good: `SRC:openai_pricing_2026`, `SRC:techcrunch_funding_april`, `SRC:gdpr_article_17`
- Bad: `SRC:source1`, `SRC:link`, `SRC:ref`

**Registry structure:**

```json
{
  "SRC:openai_pricing_2026": {
    "url": "https://openai.com/pricing",
    "title": "OpenAI API Pricing",
    "fetched_at": "2026-04-13",
    "quote": "GPT-4o: $2.50 / 1M input tokens"
  },
  "SRC:techcrunch_funding_april": {
    "url": "https://techcrunch.com/2026/04/01/acme-raises-50m",
    "title": "Acme Raises $50M Series B",
    "fetched_at": "2026-04-13",
    "quote": "focused on enterprise compliance workflows"
  }
}
```

**Before adding a new entry, check if the URL already exists in the registry.** If it does, reuse the existing ID — do not create a duplicate. Two IDs pointing to the same URL cause drift and confuse resolution.

**Write cadence:** Write the registry to disk using the Write tool after each new source is added. If the file does not exist yet, create it with an empty JSON object `{}` before the first write. If the Write tool fails, stop and report the error — do not continue research without a working registry file, as sources will be lost.

**Failed fetches:** If WebFetch returns an error, a 4xx/5xx status, or clearly partial/blocked content (e.g. a paywall), do not register it as a valid source. Instead, note it as `[SRC:MISSING — fetch failed: brief description]` in your draft. A failed fetch registered as valid is a different kind of bad link.

**Hard rule: Never write a raw URL (`https://...`) anywhere — not in the draft, not in prose, not in footnotes. Register it, then cite by ID.**

---

## Phase 2 — Writing: Fact IDs Only

Write the entire document using only registered IDs as citations. Claude's job is complete after this step.

**Example:**
> OpenAI charges $2.50 per million input tokens for GPT-4o [SRC:openai_pricing_2026], making it the most cost-effective frontier model for this use case [SRC:techcrunch_funding_april].

**If a citation is needed but no source has been fetched:**
- Write `[SRC:MISSING — brief description of what's needed]`
- Do NOT guess a URL, construct one from memory, or skip the citation silently

`[SRC:MISSING]` entries are loud and grep-able. A visible failure is always better than a silently published hallucination.

**Claude stops here. Do not attempt to resolve IDs yourself.**

---

## Phase 3 — Resolution: Python Script (No AI)

Run the following script to mechanically substitute all `[SRC:id]` placeholders with proper Markdown links. Claude does not participate in this step.

```python
import json, re, sys

def resolve_fact_ids(draft_path: str, registry_path: str, output_path: str):
    with open(draft_path, "r") as f:
        draft = f.read()
    with open(registry_path, "r") as f:
        registry = json.load(f)

    missing = []

    def replace(match):
        fact_id = match.group(1)  # e.g. "SRC:openai_pricing_2026"
        if fact_id in registry:
            url = registry[fact_id]["url"]
            title = registry[fact_id]["title"]
            return f"[{title}]({url})"
        else:
            missing.append(fact_id)
            return f"[BROKEN LINK: {fact_id}]"

    resolved = re.sub(r'\[(SRC:[^\]]+)\]', replace, draft)

    # Catch any raw URLs that leaked through — treat as errors
    raw_urls = re.findall(r'https?://\S+', resolved)
    if raw_urls:
        print(f"ERROR: Raw URLs found in resolved output (should not exist): {raw_urls}")
        sys.exit(1)

    if missing:
        print(f"WARNING: Unresolved fact IDs: {missing}")
        print("These appear as [BROKEN LINK: ...] in the output.")

    with open(output_path, "w") as f:
        f.write(resolved)

    print(f"Done. Written to {output_path}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    resolve_fact_ids(sys.argv[1], sys.argv[2], sys.argv[3])
```

**Claude runs this script using the Bash tool** — the user does not need to touch a terminal:

```bash
python3 resolve_links.py draft.md fact_registry.json final_report.md
```

Save the script as `resolve_links.py` alongside the registry file before running. The script exits with an error if any raw URLs are present in the output — catching leaks before publishing.

---

## Responsibility Boundary

| Step | Who does it | What happens |
|---|---|---|
| Fetch source | Claude (WebFetch/WebSearch) | URL stored in registry only |
| Write draft | Claude | `[SRC:id]` placeholders only — no URLs |
| Resolve links | Python script | Deterministic substitution |
| Catch leaks | Python script | Errors on any raw `https://` in output |

Claude never writes a URL at any stage. If it did, that's a bug — the script will catch it.

---

## What Never to Do

- Never write `https://...` or `http://...` directly in a draft or resolution step
- Never construct a URL from memory, even if confident ("I think it's at openai.com/blog/...")
- Never resolve `[SRC:id]` placeholders yourself — run the script instead
- Never silently omit a citation — use `[SRC:MISSING — description]`
